flowRoot.flowPara: These steps describe deploying a new S3 system to the blockchain. Each deployed system can manage as many securities as it wants, and there may be as many deployments as desired. The intention is for each entity playing the role of Digital Registrar to deploy its own instance of S3, such that it may be the authority for securities registered against it. It should be noted that Issuers themselves are welcome to deploy their own instance of S3 and thus act as their own Digital Registrar.

Cosigners are extremely important and highly protected keys owned by the issuer that may be used for administrative tasks on the contracts like contract migration, transaction clawbacks, etc. These will usually be from (separate) hardware wallets.

The controller will be the creator of the essential contracts in your deployment. It will be used to create the infrastructure, and then will be used continuously to execute issuance and delegate maintenance to issuers. It is the proverbial "key to the kingdom".

CapTables are the primary contract in S3. They represent the single source of truth regarding shareholder holdings. Each S3 deployment has its own CapTables, and each CapTables instance manages an arbitrary number of Securities.
4. Deploy new Admin Group for Issuer
The "Administration" contract defines a group of 3 cosigners, 2 of which are required for every administrative action on the security.

These steps describe issuing a new security to a deployed S3 system. Issuance is the fairly simple process of defining the essential security data in the on-chain CapTables. That essential data includes the security name, symbol, resolution (i.e., number of base units per security unit), issuer address, an admin group, a resolver, and an optional list of initial investors and their holdings.

Each Security is defined by its own instance of DelegatedTokenLogic (or more often, derivatives like SimplifiedLogic). DelegatedTokenLogic is responsible for enforcing any compliance constraints on transfers of the Security.
5. Register the Security with the CapTables Contract

CapTables are the single source of truth for shareholder holdings and gatekeeper for transfers. Each issued Security is initialized with total supply and the controller address as (initial) master, which is later changed to the address of the deployed Security contract.
Each Security uses it's own instance of TokenFront as its permanent address. Once deployed, this instance points to the Security's TokenLogic, which may be changed later on to meet evolving needs.

TokenLogic is constructed with a pointer to CapTables, and TokenFront is constructed with a pointer to TokenLogic, but we now need to complete the bindings by binding CapTables to TokenLogic and TokenLogic to TokenFront.
1. Obtain a Resolver Address from Issuer

The resolver is a key that is authorized to accept or deny transfer requests. This will typically be the key that enforces compliance criteria for transactions on this S3 deployment. (Note that compliance is an off-chain process. More on that later.)
6. Hand Over Token Inventory to Issuer
At this point, we have to transfer all holdings from controller to the issuer's inventory address.
3. Obtain an Inventory Address from Issuer
The inventory key holds all unused tokens. It has enormous value and should be guarded jealously by the issuer. It will typically be a multi-sig wallet.
10. Transfer Ownership of TokenLogic to adminGroup
The last step is to transfer ownership of the TokenLogic instance from controller to adminGroup. This delegates all administrative tasks on the security to adminGroup.

These steps describe distributing a security to initial shareholders. Once a security has been issued, the entire stock rests in the inventory account defined in section B. This inventory account should be protected and used by the business to store undistributed tokens. From here, all transactions are considered "standard flow" transactions, meaning that executing `transfer` from a given account (say, the inventory account) will queue the requested transfer for review by the resolver. On approval from the resolver, the transfer will be completed. You can easily build tooling to help facilitate future token distributions.
1. Create a Transfer Request From Inventory
To initiate distribution to one or more accounts, you'll simply call `transfer` from the inventory account. This creates a pending transfer request which must be resolved.

Just like with any other transfer request, a distribution request must be approved by the resolver. To approve the request, you'll send an instruction from the resolver account to "resolve" the transfer request. This will involve finding the pending request among the pending transfer requests first.
